              {
                "title": "4.5 Interaction with other medicinal products and other forms of interaction",
                "text": {
                  "status": "generated",
                  "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><h2>4.5 Interaction with other medicinal products and other forms of interaction</h2><p><u>Medicinal products affecting the pharmacokinetics of leniolisib</u></p><p>Leniolisib is cleared primarily through oxidative metabolism (primarily hydroxylation and dealkylation) by cytochrome P450 isoenzymes (predominantly CYP3A4, 95.4%). In a study of healthy adults, co‑administration of leniolisib and itraconazole, a strong CYP3A inhibitor, resulted in a 2‑fold increase in leniolisib exposure. Concomitant use of Joenja with strong CYP3A inhibitors should be avoided (see section 4.4).</p><p>Although co‑administration of leniolisib with strong and moderate CYP3A inducers decreased leniolisib exposure, no loss of efficacy is anticipated.</p><p><u>Combination with CYP1A2 metabolized drugs with a narrow therapeutic index</u></p><p>Time-dependent (irreversible) inhibition of CYP1A2 was observed in the presence of leniolisib <em>in vitro</em>. Clinically relevant interactions at the therapeutic dose of leniolisib (70 mg twice daily) could not be excluded for inhibition of CYP1A2.</p><p><u>Drugs that may have their exposure altered by leniolisib</u></p><p>The effect of leniolisib on BCRP, OATP1B1, and OATP1B3 substrates has not been studied clinically. <em>In vitro</em>, leniolisib is a substrate and an inhibitor of the hepatic efflux transporters OATP1B1/B3 and BCRP and is a substrate of P‑gp. Although the likelihood of an <em>in vivo</em> inhibition is low when co-administered with leniolisib, an increase in systemic exposure of drugs that are substrates of these transporters cannot be excluded. Co-administration should be avoided. As leniolisib is marginally renally excreted (6%), the observed <em>in vitro</em> inhibition on renal uptake transporters is not considered clinically relevant.</p><p><u>Gastric Acid Reducing Agents</u></p><p>Leniolisib exhibits pH-dependent solubility, with lower solubility at higher pH-values. Avoid co-administration of Joenja with locally acting antacids. Antacids should be taken either 2 hours before or 2 hours after Joenja administration.</p><p><u>Hormonal contraceptives</u></p><p>Administration of leniolisib with a single dose oral contraceptive containing ethinylestradiol and levonorgestrel increased ethinylestradiol exposure by approximately 30% with no effect on levonorgestrel exposure. The increase in ethinylestradiol exposure is unlikely to reduce the effectiveness of a combined oral contraceptive composed of ethinylestradiol and levonorgestrel.</p><p><u>Vaccines</u></p><p>No vaccine interaction studies have been performed using Joenja. Vaccinations may be less effective if administered during Joenja treatment.</p><p><u>Paediatric population</u></p><p>Interaction studies have only been performed in adults.</p></div></div>"
                }
              },
              {
                "title": "4.6 Fertility, pregnancy and lactation",
                "text": {
                  "status": "generated",
                  "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><h2>4.6 Fertility, pregnancy and lactation</h2><p><a id=\"_Hlk100920025\"></a><u>Women of childbearing potential/Contraception</u></p><p>Based on findings in animals, women of childbearing potential must use highly effective methods of contraception during treatment with Joenja and for 1 week after the last dose (see section 5.3).</p><p><u>Pregnancy</u></p><p>There are no data from the use of leniolisib in pregnant women. Embryonic and foetal development toxicity studies showed teratogenic effects of leniolisib in rats and rabbits <a id=\"_Hlk100920015\"></a>(see section 5.3). Joenja should be discontinued during pregnancy or in women of childbearing potential not using highly effective methods of contraception.</p><p><a id=\"_Hlk100920302\"></a><u>Breast‑feeding</u></p><p>It is unknown whether leniolisib and its metabolites are excreted in human milk. A risk to <a id=\"_Hlk100920293\"></a>newborn infants/infants and toddlers cannot be excluded. Breast‑feeding should be discontinued during treatment with Joenja.</p><p><u>Fertility</u></p><p>No human data on the effect of leniolisib on fertility are available. In rats, slight effects on the male reproductive organs were observed and were partially to fully reversible within a 4-week recovery period. These effects did not reduce fertility indices or pregnancy rates (see section 5.3).</p></div></div>"
