                  ]
                },
                "text": {
                  "status": "generated",
                  "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><h2>4.8 Undesirable effects</h2><p><u>Summary of safety profile</u></p><p>Safety data for leniolisib in APDS patients were obtained from two studies, Study 2201, a 2-part study and Study 2201E1. Study 2201 Part 1 (N=6) was an open‑label, within‑patient, up-titration, dose‑finding study evaluating leniolisib 10 mg, 30 mg, and 70 mg twice daily for 4 weeks per dose level to establish the safety and pharmacokinetics of leniolisib, as well as to select the optimal dose for use in Part 2. No patients from Part 1 were enrolled in Part 2<a id=\"_Hlk113036153\"></a>. Part 2 was a 12‑week randomized, blinded, placebo‑controlled study of leniolisib 70 mg twice daily in 31 patients. Twenty‑one patients were treated with leniolisib, and 10 received placebo. Additional safety data was obtained from Study 2201E1, a long-term open-label extension study in 37 patients. A total of 38 unique APDS patients received leniolisib in these clinical trials.</p><p>The most commonly reported adverse reactions during leniolisib treatment were weight increased, atopic dermatitis, fatigue, dyspepsia, vomiting, and headache.</p><p>No significant differences in the incidence of adverse reactions were observed for APDS patients by disease type, age, or gender.</p><p>No adverse drug reactions were reported in Study 2201 Part 1.</p><p><u>Tabulated list of adverse reactions</u></p><p>Table 1 lists the adverse drug reactions reported with leniolisib in Study 2201 Part 2 and Study 2201E1. Listed adverse reactions are divided into groups according to the MedDRA system organ class and frequency. Frequencies are defined as follows: very common (≥1/10), common (≥1/100 to &lt;1/10), uncommon (≥1/1,000 to &lt;1/100), rare (≥1/10,000 to &lt;1/1,000), and not known (cannot be estimated from the available data). Within each frequency grouping, adverse reactions are presented in order of decreasing seriousness.</p><p><strong>Table 1 Adverse drug reactions reported in clinical studies</strong></p><table><tr><td><p><strong>MedDRA System Organ Class</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Frequency</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Adverse reaction</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Investigations</p></td><td><p>Common</p></td><td><p>Weight increased</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gastrointestinal disorders</p></td><td><p>Common</p></td><td><p>Dyspepsia</p><p>Vomiting </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>General disorders and administration site conditions</p></td><td><p>Common</p></td><td><p>Fatigue</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nervous system disorders</p></td><td><p>Common</p></td><td><p>Headache</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Skin and subcutaneous tissue disorders</p></td><td><p>Common</p></td><td><p>Atopic dermatitis</p></td></tr></table><p><u>Reporting of suspected adverse reactions</u></p><p>Reporting suspected adverse reactions after authorisation of the medicinal product is important. It allows continued monitoring of the benefit/risk balance of the medicinal product. Healthcare professionals are asked to report any suspected adverse reactions via the national reporting system listed in <a href=\"http://www.ema.europa.eu/docs/en_GB/document_library/Template_or_form/2013/03/WC500139752.doc\"><u>Appendix V</u></a>.</p></div></div>"
                }
