            },
            "text": {
              "status": "generated",
              "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><h2>5. PHARMACOLOGICAL PROPERTIES</h2><p></p></div></div>"
            },
            "section": [
              {
                "title": "5.1 Pharmacodynamic properties",
                "text": {
                  "status": "generated",
                  "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\"><h2>5.1 Pharmacodynamic properties</h2><p><a id=\"_Hlk100921852\"></a>Pharmacotherapeutic group: <a id=\"_Hlk100921914\"></a>{group}, ATC code: {code} not yet assigned</p><p><u>Mechanism of action and Pharmacodynamic effects</u></p><p>Leniolisib is an orally bioavailable small-molecule inhibitor of p110δ that selectively inhibits the PI3Kδ enzyme. This disease-modifying mechanism of action inhibits the key signalling pathway that leads to increased production of PIP3, hyperactivity of the PI3K/ pathway, and subsequent deficiencies and dysregulation of B and T cells that give rise to the main clinical phenotypes of the activated phosphoinositide 3-kinase syndrome (APDS). Leniolisib has a 28-fold greater selectivity for PI3Kδ over PI3Kα, a 43-fold greater for PI3Kδ over PI3Kβ, and 257-fold greater selectivity for PI3Kδ over PI3Kγ. Leniolisib reduces phosphorylated AKT (pAKT) pathway overactivity in APDS-affected B and T cells, <em>ex vivo</em>.</p><p><u>Clinical efficacy and safety</u></p><p>Joenja was evaluated in a single study (Study 2201) in APDS patients with genetically activated PI3K. The study consisted of two parts. Part 1 (N=6) was an open‑label, within‑patient dose‑finding study designed to establish the safety and pharmacokinetics of leniolisib in the target APDS population, as well as to select the optimal dose to be tested in Part 2. Part 2 was a 12-week randomised, blinded, placebo-controlled study of leniolisib 70 mg twice daily in 31 patients to assess the efficacy and safety of leniolisib in the target APDS population. Eligible patients were able to continue in a long-term safety extension study (Study 2201E1).</p><p>Study 2201 recruited patients aged 12 to 75 years in Europe and North America. A total of 32 patients were screened and 31 were randomized 2:1 to receive either leniolisib 70 mg (N=21) or placebo (N=10) twice a day for 12 weeks.</p><p>In Study 2201 Part 2, the co-primary endpoints were the improvement in immune dysregulation, as measured by change from baseline in the log10‑transformed sum of product diameters (SPD) of index lesions, and the normalisation of immunophenotype as measured by the percentage of naïve B cells out of total B cells. The difference in adjusted mean change in log10-transformed SPD for leniolisib (N=18) compared to placebo (N=8) was -0.24 (CI95, -0.37, -0.11; p=0.0012). The difference in adjusted mean change in percent naïve B cells for leniolisib (N=8) compared to placebo (N=5) was 40.13 (CI95, 28.51, 51.75; p&lt;0.0001).</p><p>Improvement in both co‑primary efficacy measures was also statistically and clinically significant when adjusting for use of IgG at Baseline. Results are presented in Table 2 below:</p><table><thead><tr><th colspan=\"8\"><p><a id=\"_Ref86232620\"></a><a id=\"_Ref95982108\"></a><a id=\"_Toc87877118\"></a><a id=\"_Toc97116042\"></a><a id=\"_Toc98136890\"></a>Table 2 Primary Analysis of Change from Baseline at Week 12 (Day 85), Pharmacodynamic Analysis Set</p></th></tr><tr><th rowspan=\"2\"></th><th rowspan=\"2\"><p><strong>n</strong></p></th><th colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\"><p><strong>Adjusted Mean Change (SE)</strong></p></th><th colspan=\"4\"><p><strong>Comparison of Adjusted Means</strong></p><p><strong>Leniolisib vs Placebo</strong></p></th></tr><tr><th><p><strong>Diff</strong></p></th><th><p><strong>SE</strong></p></th><th><p><strong>(95% CI)</strong></p></th><th><p><strong>2-side p‑value</strong></p></th></tr><tr><th colspan=\"8\"><p><strong>Log<sub>10</sub>‑transformed SPD of Index Lesions (excluding patients with 0 lesions at Baseline, or SPD=0 at Day 85)</strong></p></th></tr><tr><th><p>Leniolisib 70 mg bid</p></th><th><p>18</p></th><th><p>-0.27</p></th><th><p>(0.04)</p></th><th rowspan=\"2\"><p>-0.25</p></th><th rowspan=\"2\"><p>0.06</p></th><th rowspan=\"2\"><p>(-0.38, -0.12)</p></th><th rowspan=\"2\"><p>0.0006</p></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>Placebo</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>-0.02</p></td><td><p>(0.06)</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"8\"><p><strong>Percentage of naïve B cells out of total B cells (patients with &lt;48% of naïve B cells at Baseline)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Leniolisib 70 mg bid</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>37.39</p></td><td><p>(5.35)</p></td><td><p>37.30</p></td><td><p>5.74</p></td><td><p>(24.06, 50.54)</p></td><td><p>0.0002</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Placebo</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>0.09</p></td><td><p>(6.66)</p></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"8\"><p>ANCOVA=analysis of covariance; bid=twice daily; CI=confidence interval; Diff=difference (leniolisib minus placebo); <a id=\"_Hlk97640651\"></a>SE=standard error; SPD=sum of product diameters<br />Note: ANCOVA model with treatment as a fixed effect and log<sub>10</sub>-transformed Baseline SPD as covariate. The use of glucocorticoids and IgG at Baseline were both included as categorical (yes/no) covariates. Baseline is defined as the arithmetic mean of the Baseline and Day 1 values when both are available, and if either Baseline or the Day 1 value is missing, the existing value is used.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Secondary endpoints supported the primary endpoints. Log10-transformed 3D volume of measurable non-index lesions had significantly greater reductions with leniolisib than with placebo (p=0.0033) although change in log10-transformed 3D volume of index lesions were similar (excluding patients with 0 lesions at baseline, or 100% reduction in 3D volume at day 85). A reduction in the volume and bi-dimensional size of the spleen was statistically greater with leniolisib than with placebo (p=0.0020 and p=0.0148, respectively).</p><p>Patient-reported outcomes were similar between leniolisib and placebo after 12 weeks of treatment. Mean improvement in patient-reported outcomes (quality of life as measured by Short Form 36 (SF‑36), APDS-related well-being as measured by Patient’s Global Assessment-Visual analogue scales (PtGA), and Work Productivity Activity Impairment plus Classroom Impairment Questionnaire (WPAI)) exceeded meaningful change thresholds by one year of therapy.</p><p>No increase in cytomegalovirus (CMV) or Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) viremia markers were observed during treatment.</p><p><em>Serum immunoglobulin M</em></p><p>Exploratory analysis of serum immunoglobulin M (IgM) demonstrated levels in individual patients decreasing between 24 to 54% by the end of the 12-week treatment period for a mean change of ‑33.52% in the leniolisib group vs 2.99% in the placebo group. A post hoc external comparison of IgM levels between Study 2201E1 and current practice (physician’s choice of treatment, in some cases including immunosuppressants such as sirolimus) in the European Society of Immunodeficiency Registry, balanced using inverse probability of treatment weighting, demonstrated a significantly greater (p=0.0012) reduction in IgM with leniolisib compared with current practice.</p><p><em>Durable efficacy</em></p><p>Thirty-five of the patients enrolled in Study 2201 Parts 1 and 2, and two additional patients not treated in Study 2201 but previously treated with a different PI3Kδ inhibitor, continued in Study 2201E1 and were evaluable for maintenance of response. Mean duration of leniolisib treatment was approximately 2 years, and 3 patients had more than 5 years of leniolisib exposure. There was a durable effect in continued reduction of lymphoproliferation and increases in naïve to total B cells and decrease and then levelling off of transitional B cells from Baseline to Week 36. Additionally, there were clinically meaningful reductions in infection rates (p=0.0040), accompanied by post hoc observation of reduction in immunoglobulin replacement therapy.</p><p><u>Paediatric population</u></p><p>For adolescents aged 12‑17 years, please see above. The European Medicines Agency has deferred the obligation to submit the results of studies with leniolisib in one or more subsets of the paediatric population in APDS (see section 4.2 for information on paediatric use).</p></div></div>"
